<div class="govuk-grid-row">
  <div class="govuk-grid-column-two-thirds">
    

      <div id="contents" class="app-c-contents-list-with-body">
    
      
<div class="gem-c-govspeak govuk-govspeak direction-ltr" data-module="govspeak">
      <div class="govspeak">
<p>The Government Procurement Agreement (GPA) is an agreement between 20 members of the World Trade Organization (WTO). The GPA allows UK businesses to bid for government contracts in other countries, and foreign businesses to bid for contracts in the UK.</p>

<p>At present, the UK is signed up to the GPA through EU membership. If there’s a no-deal Brexit, the UK expects to join the GPA on the same terms, independently.</p>

<p>It may take up to 30 days after exit day before this comes fully into force. The impact of this on businesses should be minimal. UK businesses will still have access to government procurements in most overseas markets. They may temporarily lose some rights provided by the GPA.</p>

<p>If you’re concerned about bidding on a foreign government procurement shortly after exit day, <a rel="external" href="https://www.great.gov.uk/eu-exit-news/contact/">please get in touch</a>.</p>

<div class="call-to-action">
<p>Read the <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/public-sector-procurement-after-a-no-deal-brexit">government guidance on public-sector procurement</a> after a no-deal Brexit.</p>
</div>

<div class="call-to-action">
<p><a rel="external" href="https://www.great.gov.uk/eu-exit-news/contact/">Contact us</a> if you have any questions.</p>
</div>

<div class="call-to-action">
